commitResults.messageTitle: Add Phone field to Property model
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property model did not have a dedicated field for phone numbers,
which limited its ability to store contact information for property
listings.

Having a phone field in the model enhances the functionality, allowing
us to store and validate phone numbers associated with properties.

Let’s introduce the Phone class in the model and add
corresponding unit tests to ensure phone numbers are handled correctly.

Adding the tests ensures future modifications can be validated without
errors, improving code reliability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add Location field to Property model
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property model did not previously include a Location field, limiting
its ability to store geographical or address-related information.

Adding a Location field to the model allows properties to have specific
locations attached, improving the ability to represent real-world
properties accurately.

Let’s introduce the Location class to handle this functionality and
include corresponding unit tests to ensure the Location logic is
correctly implemented.

The tests will validate future changes to the Location field, improving
the overall robustness of the code.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add custom exceptions for property handling
commitResults.messageBody:
Property model does not have any exceptions to handle errors

Let's improve error handling in the Property model by adding two custom
exceptions: DuplicatePropertyException and PropertyNotFoundException.

DuplicatePropertyException handles cases where an attempt is made to
add a property that already exists, ensuring no duplicate entries are
allowed. PropertyNotFoundException is used when a requested property
cannot be found, improving the clarity of error messages and making
debugging easier.

These custom exceptions will ensure more robust handling of property
management and provide clearer feedback to the user when errors occur.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add LandlordName field to Property model
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property model lacked a field to store the landlord’s name, which is
important for identifying the owner of a property in the system.

The addition of the LandlordName class allows properties to be
associated with a specific landlord, improving the data completeness
for property records.

Let’s add the LandlordName class and its corresponding unit tests to
ensure correct behavior and validation of the landlord’s name field.

These tests will ensure future changes to the LandlordName logic are
properly validated, enhancing the model’s reliability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix bug in equals() method in LocationTest
commitResults.messageBody:
The equals() method in the LocationTest class contained a bug that
caused incorrect comparisons between Location objects, leading to
failing test cases.

This bug has been fixed to ensure the equals() method correctly
compares Location instances based on their fields, improving the
accuracy of equality checks.

The fix ensures that future comparisons of Location objects in test
cases will behave as expected, resulting in more reliable test outcomes.

The PhoneTest class incorrectly imported the Person.Phone class
instead of the intended Property.Phone class. This caused tests to
fail due to mismatched types.

The import has been corrected to use the Property.Phone class, ensuring
that the test cases are properly referencing the right Phone class in
the property model.

This fix ensures that the tests will now execute correctly, improving
the overall reliability and correctness of the test suite.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add AskingPrice field to Property model
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property model previously lacked a field to store the asking price
of a property, which is crucial for representing real estate listings
accurately.

The addition of the AskingPrice class allows properties to be
associated with a specific price, improving the ability to manage and
display property information.

Let’s add the AskingPrice class along with the corresponding unit
tests to ensure proper validation and functionality of the price field.

The tests ensure that future changes related to property pricing can be
properly validated, enhancing the robustness of the system.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename isValidAddress() to isValidLocation() in LocationTest
commitResults.messageBody:
The method isValidAddress() in the LocationTest class was
incorrectly named, as it tested the validity of a Location object
rather than an address.

To improve code clarity and better reflect its functionality, the
method has been renamed to isValidLocation().

This change ensures that the method name accurately represents the
validation it performs, making the code easier to understand and
maintain.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add PropertyType field to Property model : The Property model did not previously include a field to represent the type of property (e.g., apartment, house, commercial), limiting the ability to categorize properties accurately.
commitResults.messageBody:
The addition of the PropertyType class provides a way to categorize
properties based on type, enhancing the system’s ability to manage and
display property information more effectively.

Let’s introduce the PropertyType class and its corresponding unit
tests to validate the functionality and ensure the type is properly
handled in the property model.

These tests will help ensure future changes to the property type logic
are correctly validated, improving code reliability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix incorrect Javadoc comments in AskingPrice and Location classes
commitResults.messageBody:
The Javadoc comments in the AskingPrice and Location classes were
incorrectly referring to validations unrelated to their respective
fields.

In AskingPrice.java, the comment stated that it validated phone
numbers instead of asking prices, and in Location.java, the comment
referred to email validation instead of location validation.

These comments have been corrected to accurately describe the
validation logic for asking prices and locations, improving the
clarity of the code documentation.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add Property class for improved property management
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property class has been added to enhance the model’s
ability to represent real estate properties within the system.

This change includes defining the necessary attributes for a property,
such as address, price, and type, enabling better management and
representation of properties in the system.

The update lays the groundwork for future improvements and ensures that
the model aligns with current business requirements.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename getPersonType() to getPropertyType() in Property class
commitResults.messageBody:
The getPersonType() method in the Property class was incorrectly
named, as it was intended to retrieve the property type rather than
a person type.

This method has been renamed to getPropertyType() to accurately
reflect its functionality, improving the clarity and maintainability
of the code.

This change ensures that the method name is consistent with the rest
of the class and avoids confusion in future development.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add PropertyBuilder utility class for constructing Property objects in tests
commitResults.messageBody:
Creating Property objects in tests required repetitive code, which
made the test suite harder to maintain and read.

To address this, a PropertyBuilder utility class has been introduced
to streamline the creation of Property objects with configurable
attributes. This reduces redundancy and improves the clarity of the
tests.

Let’s add the PropertyBuilder class, allowing for easier configuration
and setup of test cases involving Property objects.

This change enhances test efficiency and maintains consistency when
creating Property instances across multiple test cases.
Add meet up timing highlighting

commitResults.messageTitle: Add TypicalProperties class and update CommandTestUtil
commitResults.messageBody:
Test cases involving Property objects previously lacked a central
repository of typical property examples, leading to repetitive and
inconsistent test setups.

To address this, the TypicalProperties class has been introduced,
providing a collection of commonly used Property instances for
reusable and consistent test setups.

Additionally, CommandTestUtil has been updated to integrate these
typical properties, simplifying test case creation and ensuring
consistency across different command tests.

Let’s introduce the TypicalProperties class and update
CommandTestUtil to streamline test case setup and improve the
clarity and reliability of property-related tests.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add unit tests for Property class
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property class did not have dedicated unit tests, which made it
challenging to verify its correctness and behavior during changes or
updates.

To improve test coverage and ensure the reliability of the Property
class, PropertyTest.java has been added. This file includes various
test cases to validate the functionality and attributes of the
Property class.

Let’s add these unit tests to ensure future modifications to the
Property class are properly validated, improving overall code quality
and stability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Fix PhoneTest to reference correct model and improve test cases
commitResults.messageBody:
The PhoneTest file previously referenced the incorrect model
(person.Phone) instead of the intended property.Phone. This
caused tests to fail due to mismatched references.

The test cases have been updated to reference property.Phone, ensuring
that the correct model is being tested.

Additionally, improvements were made to the test cases by adjusting the
assertions for invalid and valid phone numbers, improving the
accuracy of test coverage.

These changes ensure that future tests involving Phone objects are
executed correctly, improving test reliability.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add UniquePropertyList to manage unique property entries
commitResults.messageBody:
The property management system requires a way to ensure that no
duplicate properties are added to the list. To address this, the
UniquePropertyList class has been introduced.

This class enforces the uniqueness of properties in the list,
preventing duplicate entries and ensuring the integrity of the property
data.

Let’s add the UniquePropertyList class to handle property collections
and maintain the uniqueness of property records, improving the
consistency and reliability of the system.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update isSameProperty method to compare property type
commitResults.messageBody:
The isSameProperty method in the Property class was previously
comparing landlord name, phone, and location to determine if two
properties were the same. However, property type was not included
in the comparison, leading to potential inconsistencies.

The method has been updated to include propertyType in the comparison
logic, ensuring that properties with the same landlord, phone, and
location but different types are no longer considered the same.

This update ensures a more accurate comparison between properties,
improving the system’s reliability when identifying unique properties.

commitResults.messageTitle: Remove incorrect test methods from PropertyTest
commitResults.messageBody:
Several test methods in PropertyTest.java were incorrectly implemented,
leading to unreliable and misleading test results. These methods did not
accurately reflect the functionality they were supposed to test.

The incorrect test methods have been removed to prevent false positives
and improve the overall reliability of the test suite.

This change ensures that only valid and accurate tests remain in
PropertyTest, improving test coverage and reliability moving forward.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add PropertyList, ReadOnlyPropertyList, and update UniquePropertyList
commitResults.messageBody:
The property management system requires several classes to handle
different lists of properties effectively.

* The PropertyList class has been added to manage a modifiable list
of properties, providing functionality to add, remove, and modify
properties.
* The ReadOnlyPropertyList class ensures that a property list can be
accessed without modifications, providing a secure way to access
property data when modification is not required.
* The UniquePropertyList class has been updated to enforce property
uniqueness within the list, preventing duplicates and ensuring data
integrity.

These changes improve the structure and handling of property lists,
enhancing the reliability and flexibility of property management
in the system.
Finish find command for meet ups

commitResults.messageTitle: Add support for Properties in UserPrefs and ReadOnlyUserPrefs
commitResults.messageBody:
Support for handling properties has been added to both the UserPrefs
class and the ReadOnlyUserPrefs interface to enhance user preference
management.

* The UserPrefs class has been updated to store and manage
property-related preferences, allowing for better customization
of user settings specific to properties.
* The ReadOnlyUserPrefs interface has been modified to include
methods that provide read-only access to property-related
preferences, ensuring that property settings are accessible
without risk of modification.

These changes improve the system’s ability to manage property-specific
user preferences, enhancing both flexibility and security when
handling user configurations.

commitResults.messageTitle: Enable support for Property management in Model class
commitResults.messageBody:
The Model class has been updated to enable support for managing
Property objects within the system. This change enhances the
model’s ability to handle property-related functionality alongside
existing features.

Key changes include:
* Added a Predicate<Property> named PREDICATE_SHOW_ALL_PROPERTIES
to allow the display and filtering of all properties.
* Introduced methods to manage property list paths and data, including
getPropertyListFilePath(), setPropertyListFilePath(), and
setPropertyList().

These updates allow for effective management of property-related data,
improving the model’s overall flexibility and robustness in handling
various components.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename hasBuyer() to hasProperty() in PropertyList
commitResults.messageBody:
The method hasBuyer() in the PropertyList class was incorrectly
named, as it was intended to check for the existence of a property
rather than a buyer.

The method has been renamed to hasProperty() to more accurately
reflect its purpose, which is to check if a property with the same
identity exists in the property list.

This change improves the clarity and accuracy of the method name,
ensuring that future developers can easily understand its function.

commitResults.messageTitle: Update MainApp, Model, and ModelManager to support Property
commitResults.messageBody:
Body:
The system has been updated to add support for managing Property
objects. This involved changes across several key classes:

1. MainApp: Updated to initialize and manage property-related data
alongside existing features, ensuring smooth integration of
property management functionality.
2. Model: Modified to support Property operations, including
handling property lists, file paths, and predicates for displaying
properties.
3. ModelManager: Adjusted to manage property data within the model,
ensuring proper coordination between the model and the application’s
property management components.

These updates enable comprehensive support for managing Property
objects, enhancing the system’s ability to handle various components
effectively.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refactor TypicalProperties and add getTypicalPropertyList method
commitResults.messageBody:
The TypicalProperties class has been refactored to improve package
organization and functionality.

The class has been moved to the seedu.address.testutil.property
package to align with other property-related utility classes,
improving the structure and consistency of the codebase.
A new method getTypicalPropertyList() has been added, which
returns a PropertyList populated with typical properties. This
method simplifies the creation of PropertyList instances for
testing purposes by utilizing the existing getTypicalProperties()
method to add properties to the list.

These changes improve the organization and usability of the
TypicalProperties class, making it easier to manage typical property
data in test cases.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add CLI syntax for property fields in CliSyntax.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The CLI syntax has been updated to support additional property-related
fields, enabling better user input handling for property management
commands.

Key changes include:
* Adding PREFIX_ASKING_PRICE, PREFIX_LOCATION, and
PREFIX_TYPE for managing properties in CLI commands.
* Updating PREFIX_BUDGET to use a new prefix "b/" instead of "a/",
ensuring consistency and avoiding conflicts with other prefixes.

These changes improve the CLI’s ability to handle property data,
enabling more accurate and user-friendly input for property-related
operations.

A new AddCommand has been implemented in the property package to
enable the addition of properties to the system through CLI commands.

This command allows users to add property records with relevant
fields, such as asking price, location, and property type, improving
the system’s functionality for property management.

The addition of this command ensures that properties can be efficiently
and accurately added, making the system more robust and user-friendly
for property management tasks.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add property-related messages and formatting to Messages.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The Messages.java file has been updated to support property-related
messages and formatting, improving the user feedback and display
capabilities for property management.

Key changes include:
* Added MESSAGE_INVALID_PROPERTY_INDEX and
MESSAGE_PROPERTIES_LISTED_OVERVIEW to handle invalid property index
errors and display a summary of listed properties.
* Implemented a format(Property property) method to format property
details for user display, including property name, phone, location,
asking price, and type.

These updates enhance the system’s ability to provide clear and
informative messages related to property management, improving
user experience.

A new DeleteCommand has been implemented in the property package to
enable the deletion of properties to the system through CLI commands.

This command allows users to delete property records given the index of
the property in the property list, improving the system’s functionality for
property management.

The addition of this command ensures that properties can be efficiently
and accurately deleted, making the system more robust and user-friendly
for property management tasks.

Property details previously could not be edited once added to the system,
which limited the flexibility in managing property data.

To address this, the EditCommand has been implemented, allowing
users to modify property details such as asking price, location, and
property type.

Let’s introduce the EditCommand to enable users to update existing
property records more effectively, making property management more
dynamic and user-friendly.

This change improves the flexibility of managing property data, allowing
modifications without the need to recreate property entries.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add FindCommand and NameContainsKeywordsPredicate for property search
commitResults.messageBody:
The system previously lacked a command to search properties by name,
which limited the ability to filter properties based on specific criteria.

To address this, the FindCommand and the
NameContainsKeywordsPredicate have been introduced. These additions
allow users to search for properties by specifying keywords in the
property name, enhancing the system’s functionality for property
search.

Let’s introduce the FindCommand and the associated predicate class to
enable users to easily find properties based on name keywords, improving
the usability of the system for property management.

This enhancement allows for more dynamic and efficient property search
capabilities, making it easier to find specific property entries.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add parsing logic for property fields in ParserUtil.java
commitResults.messageBody:
The ParserUtil.java file has been updated to support the parsing of
various property-related fields, improving the system’s ability to handle
property input from users.

Key changes:
* Added methods to parse and validate property fields such as
LandlordName, Phone, and other property-related data, ensuring
proper input validation and error handling.
* Imports related to property fields, including AskingPrice, Location,
and PropertyType, have been added to support property parsing logic.

These enhancements improve the parsing and validation of property-related
fields, ensuring better input management and validation for property
operations within the system.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add AddCommandParser for property management commands
commitResults.messageBody:
The AddCommandParser has been implemented to handle parsing logic for
the AddCommand related to property management. This parser processes
user inputs and converts them into the necessary fields for adding a
property to the system.

By introducing the AddCommandParser, the system can now efficiently
handle and validate property-related fields such as landlord name, phone
number, location, asking price, and property type.

This addition enhances the system’s ability to process user inputs for
property management commands, improving the overall user experience
and functionality for property-related operations.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add DeleteCommandParser for property deletion functionality
commitResults.messageBody:
The DeleteCommandParser has been implemented to handle parsing logic
for the DeleteCommand related to property management. This parser
processes user inputs to validate and convert them into the necessary
format for deleting a property from the system.

By introducing the DeleteCommandParser, the system can now efficiently
handle the deletion of properties by parsing relevant inputs such as
property identifiers, ensuring accurate property removal.

This addition improves the system’s ability to manage property deletion
operations, enhancing overall functionality and user experience.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rename isAnyMeetUpFieldEdited to isAnyFieldEdited in EditCommand
commitResults.messageBody:
The method isAnyMeetUpFieldEdited() in EditCommand.java was

The method has been renamed to isAnyFieldEdited() to better reflect
its purpose of checking if any property-related field (name, phone,

This change improves the clarity and accuracy of the method name,
ensuring better readability and maintainability of the code.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add EditCommandParser for property editing functionality
commitResults.messageBody:

for the EditCommand related to property management. This parser

necessary fields for editing existing property records.

By introducing the EditCommandParser, the system can now efficiently
handle user input for modifying property details such as name, phone,
location, asking price, and property type.

This addition improves the system’s ability to manage property edits,
enhancing the overall user experience and flexibility in updating
property records.

The class NameContainsKeywordsPredicate has been renamed to
LocationContainsKeywordsPredicate to better reflect its purpose of
testing whether a property’s location matches any of the given keywords.

Key changes include:
* Renamed the class and constructor from NameContainsKeywordsPredicate
to LocationContainsKeywordsPredicate.
* Updated the predicate logic to check if any of the keywords match
the property’s location using StringUtil.containsWordIgnoreCase().
* Refactored relevant method names and equality checks to align with
the new class name.

This refactor improves clarity by ensuring the class name accurately
represents its function, which is to match keywords with property
locations rather than names.

The FindCommand has been updated to use
LocationContainsKeywordsPredicate instead of
NameContainsKeywordsPredicate to align with the shift from searching
by property names to searching by property locations.

Key changes include:
* Replaced all instances of NameContainsKeywordsPredicate with
LocationContainsKeywordsPredicate.
* Updated the FindCommand constructor to accept the new predicate
for searching properties by location.
* Adjusted relevant imports to reflect the predicate name change.

These updates ensure that the FindCommand now correctly searches for
properties based on location keywords, improving search functionality
for property management.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add FindCommandParser for property search functionality

This addition enables the system to handle user queries efficiently,
allowing for dynamic property searches based on location, improving the
user experience for property management tasks.

commitResults.messageTitle: Property class: rename getName to getLandlordName
commitResults.messageBody:
The Property class has a method getName which refers to the
landlord’s name. This naming is ambiguous, as it could be
misinterpreted as returning the property name rather than the
landlord’s name.

Ambiguous method names can lead to misunderstandings in the codebase
and potential errors during usage, especially as the project scales
and more developers interact with the code.

Let’s rename getName to getLandlordName in the Property class to
clarify that this method returns the landlord’s name.

Renaming to getLandlordName improves readability and maintains
consistency with other landlord-specific fields in the Property
class, which helps developers quickly understand the purpose of this
method.

Additionally, update all references to getName across affected files
(EditCommand, Messages, JsonAdaptedProperty, PropertyCard)
and update test files accordingly (PropertyTest,
JsonAdaptedPropertyTest, PropertyBuilder, and PropertyUtil).

commitResults.messageTitle: Update property addresses to ensure uniqueness
commitResults.messageBody:
The property addresses in test data files are the same, which may lead to
unintended overlaps or confusion during testing, reducing the accuracy of
results in scenarios where unique addresses are expected.

Let’s update the addresses in relevant test data files, including
JsonSerializablePropertyListTest, CommandTestUtil, and TypicalProperties
to use unique values. This ensures that each property instance can be
distinguished by address during tests.

Using unique addresses improves test robustness by allowing clearer
identification of specific properties and preventing accidental
interference between test cases.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refine isSameProperty to focus on address equality
commitResults.messageBody:
The isSameProperty method currently compares multiple fields, including
LandlordName, Address, and PropertyType, to determine if two property
instances are considered the same.

Multiple fields in the comparison may lead to properties not matching as
expected, especially in scenarios where only the address should be used to
determine uniqueness.

Let’s refine isSameProperty to check only the Address field, as it is a
more definitive identifier for a property.

This approach simplifies identity checking, making it easier to identify
properties uniquely based on their address alone.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add unit tests for isSameProperty and equals methods
commitResults.messageBody:
The isSameProperty and equals methods currently lack dedicated unit
tests, which limits the verification of their expected behavior and
potential edge cases.

A lack of testing may lead to undetected issues or unexpected behavior,
especially as changes are made to how property identity and equality are
defined.

Let’s add unit tests for isSameProperty to ensure it checks only the
address for property identity, and for equals to verify comprehensive
property equality across all fields.

This approach strengthens test coverage and ensures correctness in
property comparisons.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add unit tests for PropertyList class
commitResults.messageBody:
The PropertyList class lacks comprehensive unit tests, which makes it
challenging to verify expected behaviors, especially around property
management and exception handling.

Testing for duplicate properties, null handling, list immutability,
and string representation will help catch issues early.

Let’s add tests to verify list reset behavior, duplicate property
exceptions, and immutability of the returned property list.

This approach enhances test coverage for PropertyList, helping ensure
reliable functionality and adherence to expected behaviors.

UniquePropertyList’s remove method throws a MeetUpNotFoundException
when attempting to remove a property that doesn’t exist in the list.
This exception name does not accurately represent the context in which
it’s used.

This misalignment between exception type and context may cause confusion
for developers and hinder error tracing in property-related operations.

Let’s update the remove method in UniquePropertyList to throw a
PropertyNotFoundException instead. This change provides a more
accurate representation of the exception’s purpose.

Aligning exceptions with their contexts improves code readability and
error tracing, facilitating easier maintenance and debugging.

commitResults.messageTitle: Add unit tests for UniquePropertyList behaviors
commitResults.messageBody:
UniquePropertyList lacks comprehensive unit tests to verify the
functionality of its methods, particularly for handling unique
constraints and list modifications.

Without adequate tests, changes to UniquePropertyList may introduce
bugs that go undetected, potentially breaking list integrity and
allowing duplicate properties.

Let’s add unit tests to verify the behaviors of UniquePropertyList’s
methods. These tests cover scenarios such as adding and removing
properties, checking for duplicates, setting properties, and ensuring
the list is immutable.

These tests will help ensure UniquePropertyList maintains its intended
behavior, improving code reliability and preventing regression errors.

commitResults.messageBody:
EditCommand, PropertyTest, and UniquePropertyListTest contain

These violations can cause issues in code consistency, readability,
and maintainability, and may also lead to automated checks failing.

Let’s address these Checkstyle violations to align with the
project’s coding standards. Adjust formatting, spacing, and any
other required changes to pass Checkstyle checks.

Ensuring compliance with Checkstyle improves code quality and
makes the codebase easier to maintain.
